types.name: String
types.description: The `String` scalar type represents textual data, represented as UTF-8 character sequences. The String type is most often used by GraphQL to represent free-form human-readable text.

types.name: Int
types.description: The `Int` scalar type represents non-fractional signed whole numeric values. Int can represent values between -(2^31) and 2^31 - 1.

types.name: Float
types.description: The `Float` scalar type represents signed double-precision fractional values as specified by [IEEE 754](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IEEE_floating_point).

types.name: MessageFilter
types.description:
# Message type

           Message layout queries.  A message consists of its header followed by its
           body or payload. The body is essentially arbitrary, to be interpreted by the
           destination smart contract. It can be queried with the following fields:

inputFields.name: msg_type
inputFields.description:
Returns the type of message.
- 0 – internal
- 1 – extIn
- 2 – extOut

inputFields.name: status
inputFields.description:
Returns internal processing status according to the numbers shown.
- 0 – unknown
- 1 – queued
- 2 – processing
- 3 – preliminary
- 4 – proposed
- 5 – finalized
- 6 – refused
- 7 – transiting

inputFields.name: block_id
inputFields.description: Merkle proof that account is a part of shard state it cut from as a bag of cells with Merkle proof struct encoded as base64.

inputFields.name: body
inputFields.description: Bag of cells with the message body encoded as base64.

inputFields.name: split_depth
inputFields.description: This is only used for special contracts in masterchain to deploy messages.

inputFields.name: tick
inputFields.description: This is only used for special contracts in masterchain to deploy messages.

inputFields.name: tock
inputFields.description: This is only used for special contracts in masterchain to deploy messages

inputFields.name: code
inputFields.description: Represents contract code in deploy messages.

inputFields.name: data
inputFields.description: Represents initial data for a contract in deploy messages

inputFields.name: library
inputFields.description: Represents contract library in deploy messages

inputFields.name: src
inputFields.description: Returns source address string

inputFields.name: dst
inputFields.description: Returns destination address string

inputFields.name: src_workchain_id
inputFields.description: Workchain id of the source address (src field)

inputFields.name: dst_workchain_id
inputFields.description: Workchain id of the destination address (dst field)

inputFields.name: created_lt
inputFields.description: Logical creation time automatically set by the generating transaction.

inputFields.name: created_at
inputFields.description: Creation unixtime automatically set by the generating transaction. The creation unixtime equals the creation unixtime of the block containing the generating transaction.

inputFields.name: ihr_disabled
inputFields.description: IHR is disabled for the message.

inputFields.name: ihr_fee
inputFields.description: This value is subtracted from the value attached to the message and awarded to the validators of the destination shardchain if they include the message by the IHR mechanism.

inputFields.name: fwd_fee
inputFields.description: Original total forwarding fee paid for using the HR mechanism; it is automatically computed from some configuration parameters and the size of the message at the time the message is generated.

inputFields.name: bounce
inputFields.description: Bounce flag. If the transaction has been aborted, and the inbound message has its bounce flag set, then it is “bounced” by automatically generating an outbound message (with the bounce flag clear) to its original sender.

inputFields.name: bounced
inputFields.description: Bounced flag. If the transaction has been aborted, and the inbound message has its bounce flag set, then it is “bounced” by automatically generating an outbound message (with the bounce flag clear) to its original sender.

inputFields.name: value
inputFields.description: May or may not be present

inputFields.name: value_other
inputFields.description: May or may not be present.

inputFields.name: proof
inputFields.description: Merkle proof that message is a part of a block it cut from. It is a bag of cells with Merkle proof struct encoded as base64.

inputFields.name: boc
inputFields.description: A bag of cells with the message structure encoded as base64.

inputFields.name: storage_fees_collected
inputFields.description: This field defines the amount of storage fees collected in grams.

inputFields.name: storage_fees_due
inputFields.description: This field represents the amount of due fees in grams, it might be empty.

inputFields.name: status_change
inputFields.description:
This field represents account status change after the transaction is completed.
- 0 – unchanged
- 1 – frozen
- 2 – deleted

inputFields.name: due_fees_collected
inputFields.description: The sum of due_fees_collected and credit must equal the value of the message received, plus its ihr_fee if the message has not been received via Instant Hypercube Routing, IHR (otherwise the ihr_fee is awarded to the validators).

inputFields.name: compute_type
inputFields.description:
- 0 – skipped
- 1 – vm

inputFields.name: skipped_reason
inputFields.description:
Reason for skipping the compute phase. According to the specification, the phase can be skipped due to the absence of funds to buy gas, absence of state of an account or a message, failure to provide a valid state in the message
- 0 – noState
- 1 – badState
- 2 – noGas

inputFields.name: success
inputFields.description: This flag is set if and only if exit_code is either 0 or 1.

inputFields.name: msg_state_used
inputFields.description: This parameter reflects whether the state passed in the message has been used. If it is set, the account_activated flag is used (see below)This parameter reflects whether the state passed in the message has been used. If it is set, the account_activated flag is used (see below)

inputFields.name: account_activated
inputFields.description: The flag reflects whether this has resulted in the activation of a previously frozen, uninitialized or non-existent account.

inputFields.name: gas_fees
inputFields.description: This parameter reflects the total gas fees collected by the validators for executing this transaction. It must be equal to the product of gas_used and gas_price from the current block header.

inputFields.name: gas_limit
inputFields.description: This parameter reflects the gas limit for this instance of TVM. It equals the lesser of either the Grams credited in the credit phase from the value of the inbound message divided by the current gas price, or the global per-transaction gas limit.

inputFields.name: gas_credit
inputFields.description: This parameter may be non-zero only for external inbound messages. It is the lesser of either the amount of gas that can be paid from the account balance or the maximum gas credit

inputFields.name: exit_code
inputFields.description: These parameter represents the status values returned by TVM; for a successful transaction, exit_code has to be 0 or 1

inputFields.name: vm_steps
inputFields.description: the total number of steps performed by TVM (usually equal to two plus the number of instructions executed, including implicit RETs)

inputFields.name: vm_init_state_hash
inputFields.description: This parameter is the representation hashes of the original state of TVM.

inputFields.name: vm_final_state_hash
inputFields.description: This parameter is the representation hashes of the resulting state of TVM.

inputFields.name: no_funds
inputFields.description: The flag indicates absence of funds required to create an outbound message

inputFields.name: status_change
inputFields.description:
- 0 – unchanged
- 1 – frozen
- 2 – deleted

inputFields.name: bounce_type
inputFields.description:
- 0 – negFunds
- 1 – noFunds
- 2 – ok

inputFields.name: cur_shard_pfx_len
inputFields.description: length of the current shard prefix

types.name: QueryOrderBy
types.description:
Specify how to sort results.
You can sort documents in result set using more than one field.

inputFields.name: path
inputFields.description:
Path to field which must be used as a sort criteria.
If field resides deep in structure path items must be separated with dot (e.g. 'foo.bar.baz').

inputFields.name: direction
inputFields.description: Sort order direction

enumValues.name: ASC
enumValues.description: Documents will be sorted in ascended order (e.g. from A to Z)

enumValues.name: DESC
enumValues.description: Documents will be sorted in descendant order (e.g. from Z to A)

inputFields.name: before_split
inputFields.description:
TON Blockchain supports dynamic sharding, so the shard configuration may change from block to block because of shard merge and split events. Therefore, we cannot simply say that each shardchain corresponds to a fixed set of account chains.
A shardchain block and its state may each be classified into two distinct parts. The parts with the ISP-dictated form of will be called the split parts of the block and its state, while the remainder will be called the non-split parts.
The masterchain cannot be split or merged.

fields.name: before_split
fields.description:
TON Blockchain supports dynamic sharding, so the shard configuration may change from block to block because of shard merge and split events. Therefore, we cannot simply say that each shardchain corresponds to a fixed set of account chains.
A shardchain block and its state may each be classified into two distinct parts. The parts with the ISP-dictated form of will be called the split parts of the block and its state, while the remainder will be called the non-split parts.
The masterchain cannot be split or merged.

types.name: AccountFilter
types.description:
# Account type

Recall that a smart contract and an account are the same thing in the context
of the TON Blockchain, and that these terms can be used interchangeably, at
least as long as only small (or “usual”) smart contracts are considered. A large
smart-contract may employ several accounts lying in different shardchains of
the same workchain for load balancing purposes.

An account is identified by its full address and is completely described by
its state. In other words, there is nothing else in an account apart from its
address and state.

inputFields.name: workchain_id
inputFields.description: Workchain id of the account address (id field).

inputFields.name: acc_type
last_paid
due_payment
balance
split_depth
inputFields.description: Is present and non-zero only in instances of large smart contracts.

inputFields.name: tick
inputFields.description: May be present only in the masterchain—and within the masterchain, only in some fundamental smart contracts required for the whole system to function.

inputFields.name: tock
code
data
inputFields.description: If present, contains smart-contract data encoded with in base64.

inputFields.name: library
inputFields.description: If present, contains library code used in smart-contract.

inputFields.name: proof
inputFields.description: Merkle proof that account is a part of shard state it cut from as a bag of cells with Merkle proof struct encoded as base64.

inputFields.name: boc
inputFields.description: Bag of cells with the account struct encoded as base64.

types.name: __Schema
types.description: A GraphQL Schema defines the capabilities of a GraphQL server. It exposes all available types and directives on the server, as well as the entry points for query, mutation, and subscription operations.

fields.name: types
fields.description: A list of all types supported by this server.

fields.name: queryType
fields.description: The type that query operations will be rooted at.

fields.name: mutationType
fields.description: If this server supports mutation, the type that mutation operations will be rooted at.

fields.name: subscriptionType
fields.description: If this server support subscription, the type that subscription operations will be rooted at.

fields.name: directives
fields.description: A list of all directives supported by this server.

types.name: __Type
types.description:
The fundamental unit of any GraphQL Schema is the type. There are many kinds of types in GraphQL as represented by the `__TypeKind` enum.

Depending on the kind of a type, certain fields describe information about that type. Scalar types provide no information beyond a name and description, while Enum types provide their values. Object and Interface types provide the fields they describe. Abstract types, Union and Interface, provide the Object types possible at runtime. List and NonNull types compose other types.

types.name: __TypeKind
types.description: An enum describing what kind of type a given `__Type` is.

enumValues.name: SCALAR
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is a scalar.

enumValues.name: OBJECT
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is an object. `fields` and `interfaces` are valid fields.

enumValues.name: INTERFACE
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is an interface. `fields` and `possibleTypes` are valid fields.

enumValues.name: UNION
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is a union. `possibleTypes` is a valid field.

enumValues.name: ENUM
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is an enum. `enumValues` is a valid field.

enumValues.name: INPUT_OBJECT
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is an input object. `inputFields` is a valid field.

enumValues.name: LIST
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is a list. `ofType` is a valid field.

enumValues.name: NON_NULL
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is a non-null. `ofType` is a valid field.

types.name: __Field
types.description: Object and Interface types are described by a list of Fields, each of which has a name, potentially a list of arguments, and a return type.

types.name: __InputValue
types.description: Arguments provided to Fields or Directives and the input fields of an InputObject are represented as Input Values which describe their type and optionally a default value.

fields.name: defaultValue
fields.description: A GraphQL-formatted string representing the default value for this input value.

types.name: __EnumValue
types.description: One possible value for a given Enum. Enum values are unique values, not a placeholder for a string or numeric value. However an Enum value is returned in a JSON response as a string.

types.name: __Directive
types.description:
A Directive provides a way to describe alternate runtime execution and type validation behavior in a GraphQL document.

In some cases, you need to provide options to alter GraphQL's execution behavior in ways field arguments will not suffice, such as conditionally including or skipping a field. Directives provide this by describing additional information to the executor.

types.name: __DirectiveLocation
types.description: A Directive can be adjacent to many parts of the GraphQL language, a __DirectiveLocation describes one such possible adjacencies.

enumValues.name: QUERY
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a query operation.

enumValues.name: MUTATION
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a mutation operation.

enumValues.name: SUBSCRIPTION
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a subscription operation.

enumValues.name: FIELD
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a field.

enumValues.name: FRAGMENT_DEFINITION
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a fragment definition.

enumValues.name: FRAGMENT_SPREAD
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a fragment spread.

enumValues.name: INLINE_FRAGMENT
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to an inline fragment.

enumValues.name: VARIABLE_DEFINITION
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a variable definition.

enumValues.name: SCHEMA
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a schema definition.

enumValues.name: SCALAR
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a scalar definition.

enumValues.name: OBJECT
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to an object type definition.

enumValues.name: FIELD_DEFINITION
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a field definition.

enumValues.name: ARGUMENT_DEFINITION
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to an argument definition.

enumValues.name: INTERFACE
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to an interface definition.

enumValues.name: UNION
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a union definition.

enumValues.name: ENUM
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to an enum definition.

enumValues.name: ENUM_VALUE
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to an enum value definition.

enumValues.name: INPUT_OBJECT
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to an input object type definition.

enumValues.name: INPUT_FIELD_DEFINITION
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to an input object field definition.

types.name: Upload
types.description: The `Upload` scalar type represents a file upload.

directives.name: skip
directives.description: Directs the executor to skip this field or fragment when the `if` argument is true.

directives.name: include
directives.description: Directs the executor to include this field or fragment only when the `if` argument is true.

directives.name: deprecated
directives.description: Marks an element of a GraphQL schema as no longer supported.

args.name: reason
args.description: Explains why this element was deprecated, usually also including a suggestion for how to access supported similar data. Formatted using the Markdown syntax (as specified by [CommonMark](https://commonmark.org/).
